entry.title: Add additional check to block race condition
entry.content:
It is possible, though unlikely, for a second request to come through

*after* a request has been served (e.g. the runtime is presenting and

the request_session_callback_ has been nulled out). This request should

be rejected as there is now an active immersive session; though the

browser process may not know it yet. (e.g. the request got queued up

while the previous request was processing and so the browser process

was as yet unaware of the result).

entry.title: Allow video stream to end when paused and no frames remain.
entry.content:
The fix for https://crbug.com/935451 introduced a regression here. The

intent was to try and obey frame duration with regards to when we signal

the ended event. However when time isn't progressing, we should signal

ended right away instead of waiting until playback starts.



The HTML5 spec says: "It is possible for a media element to have both

ended playback and paused for user interaction at the same time." which

implies we should fire ended when reaching the last frame while paused.



R=liberato

entry.title: Renderers to use new interface to create GMBs.
entry.content:
1. Add a new interface ClientGmbInterface which renderers will use now

to create GpuMemoryBuffers. This new interface is a direct connection

between renderer and gpu process. This allows renderers to do IPC

directly to GPU process without routing it to browser process.



2. Both native buffers and shared memory handles are now created in GPU

Select to Speak and Switch Access both inject a content script into

Google Docs that informs Docs to annotate the canvas for a11y. This

script was not injected in Lacros browsers because STS/Switch run as

component extension in Ash.



ChromeVox injects a content script to Google Docs that informs Docs

browsers because ChromeVox runs as a component extension in Ash.



This change creates helper extensions in Lacros that will do the content

script injection for the Ash features.



In a follow up we will load these extensions for all profiles when the

relevant a11y features are enabled, and unload them when the features are

disabled. See crrev.com/c/4569470.

entry.title: [Auto-disable Accessibility] Update Clank dismiss duration to depend on AccessibilityState
entry.content:
This CL continues the work of consolidating accessibility code

in Clank into a single source and removing all other hard

dependencies on the AccessibilityManager.



With this CL we remove the AccessibilityManager dependency from

the Snackbar and ChromeMessage classes. These classes used the

getRecommendedTimeoutInMillis method to set a duration for an

auto-dismiss feature. This required Android Q or above, and an

instance of AccessibilityManager. We instead add a comparable

method in AccessibilityState which returns a multiplier, rather

than requiring a starting duration parameter. This multiplier

is cached from the AccessibilityManager whenever the

accessibility state of the device changes. It will default to

1.0, and will always be 1.0 for Android version < Q.



With this change we are able to simplify much of the logic and

remove some dependencies from the clients. They no longer need

to check Android version, and can simply call the static method

in AccessibilityState. We update tests as needed, and update

the language for the clients. The clients are interested in

whether or not accessibility services that can perform gestures

is enabled. We make this clearer in the comments/test errors.

entry.title: Remove AX relation target update during AXObject::Init
entry.content:
We should not be invalidating AX objects during tree building or

initialization of AX objects (*). All invalidation should happen

explicitly in state observer callbacks. To that end,

MaybeNewRelationTarget is already called explicitly in:

phase, such as needing to build it again due to invalidations found too late. Instead, the a11y lifecycle phase should be structured like this:

entry.title: Revert "[base] Properly detect NEON support on ARM{,64}"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 59edf62cfd5c0ec43dcb5d3d7358c5c314208f2e.



Reason for revert: crbug.com/1451553 WPT regressions



Original change's description:

> [base] Properly detect NEON support on ARM{,64}

>

> olivierli@chromium.org discovered that CPU_ARM_NEON is not defined where

> it should (in particular on ARM64). This commit fixes the detection.

>

> However, fixing this makes ARM64 builds fail. This is because of buggy

> hand-written assembly code in WTF::CopyLCharsFramUCharSource() for the

> NEON path. The path uses inline assembly to perform the char16_t -> char

> conversion in the case where all the characters in the char16_t array

> are 8-bit. This is potentially quite hot code in blink, but the code is

> broken because it uses inline assembly with incorrect registers.

>

> A clean solution would be to use intrinsics, but a lazier one is to

> trust the "sufficiently smart compiler", which indeed auto-vectorizes

> the loop at "-O2" (tested with compiler explorer, on reasonably recent

> clang versions). Since this assembly code path wasn't used before, we

> lose nothing by not using inline assembly.

>

> For reference, the error message generated when leaving the inline

> assembly as is:

>

> In file included from ../../third_party/blink/renderer/platform/wtf/text/wtf_string.cc:41:

> ../../third_party/blink/renderer/platform/wtf/text/copy_lchars_from_uchar_source.h:97:11: error: vector register expected

> asm("vld2.8 { d0-d1 }, [%[SOURCE]] !\n\t"

> ^

> :1:13: note: instantiated into assembly here

> vld2.8 { d0-d1 }, [x1] !

>

> Also need to update a webaudio fingerprinting test. The result changes

> because... floating point, and enabling NEON expectedly changes the

> results.

>

> Note for sheriffs: If there is a build breakage on ARM64 in range, this is likely the culprit.

>

entry.title: [User Education] Make help bubbles attached to menus interactable
entry.content:
Because menus capture all mouse and touch events, a help bubble anchored

to a menu cannot receive hover or click events. If the user does click

on the bubble, the menu logic registers the click outside of the menu

and closes the menu.



This means that the user effectively cannot interact with a help bubble

anchored to a menu at all (because the menu disappearing would also

destroy the help bubble).



This CL allows "annotation bubbles" to register themselves to listen for specific types of events and then handle them explicitly. It is hooked up to the help bubble system and tested.



Known issues:

- F6 still does not work with these bubbles; it is not possible to

keyboard focus them. This is mitigated by the fact that the bubbles

do not significantly interfere with the functioning of the menu if

the user follows the tutorial; they can be safely ignored.

- We could create a faux focus-tracking system if we had to bridge

this gap; it would just be more work.

- There are some z-ordering issues; care must be taken not to attach a

bubble to a menu item with a submenu unless the bubble will be

dismissed when the submenu is shown.

entry.title: Don't recursively destroy guests when clearing unattached guests
entry.content:
When an embedder process is destroyed, we also destroy any unattached

guests associated with that process. This is currently done with a

single call to `owned_guests_.erase`. However, it's possible that two

unattached guests could have an opener relationship, which causes the

destruction of the opener guest to also destroy the other guest, during

the call to `erase`, which is unsafe.



We now separate the steps of erasing `owned_guests_` and destroying the

guests, to avoid this recursive guest destruction.



This also fixes the WaitForNumGuestsCreated test method to not

return prematurely.
